The survey spectrum revealed the typical peaks from carbon, oxygen and iron of Fe3O4@SiO2@CDs (See 
                           Fig. S3A
                        ). Fig. S3B shows that there were two peaks belonging to Fe 2p1/2 and Fe 2p3/2 at 723 eV and 711 eV, and no satellite peaks at 719 eV, which proved that the magnetic core material was Fe3O4. The Gaussian fitting C1s spectra of three bands for CO, C–C/C–O and CC were located at 288.4 eV, 286.4 eV and 284.8 eV (See Fig. S3C), respectively. The O1s spectra was shown in Fig. S3D, and the resolved peaks were concentrated at 530.8 eV, 529.9 eV and 529.4 eV, which was pertaining to –OH, CO and Fe–O, respectively. These XPS data ulteriorly verified the successful synthesis of Fe3O4@SiO2@CDs.

Meanwhile, Fig. S5E analyzed the oxidation peak potential of TBBPA. It was found that the oxidation peak potential (Epa) of TBBPA shifted to the right with the continuous increasement of the scan rate. With change of scan rate ranged in 50 mV s−1 - 500 mV s−1, Epa of TBBPA and ln ν also exhibited excellent linearity, and the regression equation was Epa (V) = 0.0234 ln ν + 0.575 (R2 = 0.995). For irreversible reaction process, Epa is calculated with Laviron equation (Laviron, 1979).
